.PP
The semantics of them and their exact signatures are explained below.

.PP
Note that the data extracted from the imported (loaded) mibs are stored partly by the mib-server and partly by the symbolic-store server. See the default mib-server data module, \fIsnmpa_mib_data_tttn\fR for details.

.SH DATA TYPES
.LP
.B
\fBfilename() :: file:filename().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBmib_view() :: [mib_view_elem()].\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBmib_view_elem() ::\fR
\fB          {SubTree :: snmp:oid(),\fR
\fB           Mask :: [non_neg_integer()],\fR
\fB           Inclusion :: mib_view_inclusion()}.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBmib_view_inclusion() :: 1 | 2.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBmib_view_mask() :: [non_neg_integer()].\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.SH CALLBACKS
.LP
.B
\fBbackup(State, BackupDir)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Perform a backup of the mib-server data.

.PP
Note that its implementation dependent (and also dependent on mib-storage is used) if a backup is possible.


.RE
.B
\fBclose(State)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Close the mib-storage.


.RE
.B
\fBcode_change(Direction, Vsn, Extra, State)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Perform a code-change (upgrade or downgrade).

.PP
See \fIgen_server\fR for more info regarding the \fIVsn\fR and \fIExtra\fR arguments.


.RE
.B
\fBdump(State, Destination)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Dump the mib-server data to \fIstdio\fR (Destination = \fIio\fR) or the specified file.


.RE
.B
\fBinfo(State)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Retrieve misc info for the mib data.

.PP
This is a utility function used to inspect, for instance, memory usage, in a simple way.


.RE
.B
\fBload_mib(State, FileName, MeOverride, TeOverride)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Load the mib specified by the \fIFilename\fR argument into the mib-server. The \fIMeOverride\fR and \fITeOverride\fR arguments specifies how the mib-server shall handle duplicate mib- and trap- entries.


.RE
.B
\fBlookup(State, Oid)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Find the mib-entry corresponding to the \fIOid\fR. If it is a variable, the \fIOid\fR must be <Oid for var>.0 and if it is a table, \fIOid\fR must be


.RE
.B
\fBnew(MibStorage)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Create a new mib-server data instance.


.RE
.B
\fBnext(State, Oid, MibView)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Finds the lexicographically next oid.


.RE
.B
\fBregister_subagent(State, Oid, Pid)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Register the subagent, process, handling part of the mib-tree.


.RE
.B
\fBsync(State)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Synchronize (write to disc, if possible) the mib-server data. This depends on the \fImib_storage\fR option, and will only have an effect if the mib-storage option has an actual disc component (such as dets, or ets with a file).


.RE
.B
\fBunload_mib(State, FileName, MeOverride, TeOverride)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Unload the mib specified by the \fIFilename\fR argument from the mib-server. The \fIMeOverride\fR and \fITeOverride\fR arguments specifies how the mib-server shall handle duplicate mib- and trap- entries.


.RE
.B
\fBunregister_subagent(State, PidOrOid)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Unregister the subagent, handling part of the mib-tree, as specified by the \fIoid()\fR or \fIpid/0\fR (\fIPidOrOid\fR).

.PP
When unregister the subagent using an \fIoid()\fR, the \fIpid/0\fR of the process handling the sub-tree is also returned.


.RE
.B
\fBwhereis_mib(State, MibName)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Retrieve the mib file for the mib.


.RE
.B
\fBwhich_mib(State, Oid)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Retrieve the mib-file to which an given \fIoid()\fR belongs.


.RE
.B
\fBwhich_mibs(State)\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Retrieve all loaded mib-files.


.RE
